BoxCast hopes to become the kind of company of which movies are made



BoxCast-2.JPG
        
            The BoxCast device, about the size of a hefty smartphone, is a specialized computer that simplifies video streaming so that virtually anyone can broadcast their event online.
        
        
            
                (The Plain Dealer)



Print
Email


Robert L. Smith, The Plain Dealer

	



	



By

	
		
	
		
			
	
		
	
	
	
	
	Robert L. Smith, The Plain Dealer

The Plain Dealer
 Email the author | Follow on Twitter
on June 29, 2013 at 12:00 PM, updated July 01, 2013 at 10:58 AM









 comments

















The need for a simple way to share video was maybe best described by a funeral home director who wanted to broadcast a chapel service to people who could not be there.
	He explained to Gordon Daily and his colleagues that he had to focus on grieving family members, not cameras and computers: "Can you just make something that works automatically?" 
	Daily believes they did. 
Local startupsEmbrace Pet Insurance finds success keeping tails waggingBoxCast hopes to become the kind of company of which movies are made 
	Jumpstart Inc. just announced a $250,000 commitment to BoxCast, a Cleveland startup with a device that simplifies video streaming for the masses. It's the largest investment to date in BoxCast, a young company that some think is poised to soar. 
	Lee Poseidon, a former tech executive who advises entrepreneurs for JumpStart, calls BoxCast's video broadcast system "a potential game changer" for the new options it offers anyone with an audience to reach. 
	Online video streaming has been around for years. But it's complex and expensive enough, Daily argues, that most people don't attempt it. And so sermons go unheard, high school football games go unwatched, and countless meaningful events are missed by people who would dearly like to see them. 
 Gordon DailyCassie Tabora/The Plain Dealer The solution began brewing in 2008, when Daily and some former Case Western Reserve University classmates designed a website for Jenkins Funeral Chapel in Westlake. 
	The director asked if there was a way for family members to watch a service through the website. Team members arranged an online broadcast but they also saw larger potential. 
	"What if we could make it so simple anyone could do it?" Daily recalls thinking. "We knew this was a killer idea." 
	Fortunately, he had the skill to match his passion. Before co-founding BoxCast, the 34-year-old engineer worked as product manager and software developer at Rockwell Automation. 
 Rockwell's influences are apparent in the BoxCast device. It's a sturdy, uncomplicated black box the size of a chubby smartphone. There's no dials or buttons to confuse, only connection points for the video camera and the Internet. 
	Packed with customized microchips, the Mentor-made device is a specialized computer that captures video from a camera and sends it to the cloud, where the video is formatted by BoxCast for broadcast to online devices. 
	The technological breakthrough, Daily says, is BoxCast's ability to stream high-definition video to practically any smartphone, laptop or tablet computer. That required years of effort and lots of help. 
	A $60,000 product improvement grant from MAGNET allowed the company to design a better, cheaper, $300 version of its original model. Daily said he also benefited mightily from technical support and business guidance from Rockwell and from local entrepreneurship support groups like TECHudson and JumpStart. 
	With JumpStart's investment, the company can now focus on expanding its base of about 100 customers -- mostly church pastors and school athletic directors whose subscriptions allow them to sell or share their video as they see fit. 
	"Anybody would want to see their kid play," Daily said. "We just need to get the word out that this is possible." 
	Earlier this month, the company moved into bright, spacious offices on the second floor of the Burke Lakefront Airport Terminal. The staff recently grew from four to an even dozen, and more hires are expected. 
	As he watches planes taking off outside his office windows, Daily aims a video camera -- one equipped for streaming -- and envisions the world doing the same. 
 

































